The hook in `src/state/featureFlags/hooks/useFeatureFlag/useFeatureFlag.ts` uses a “function-in-context” pattern:

- It defines the real logic in `_useFeatureFlag` (calls `useFeatureFlags`, applies devOverrides, returns default when query pending/error).
- It creates a context `UseFeatureFlagContext` whose default value is that function.
- The public hook `useFeatureFlag` just reads the current function from context and invokes it.

Why set it up this way:
- Dependency injection: components call `useFeatureFlag` without caring where the implementation comes from; a provider can swap in a different resolver (e.g., preloaded flags, mocked flags in tests/storybook, SSR-initialized flags) without touching call sites.
- Testability/override: you can mount a tree with `UseFeatureFlagContext.Provider value={fakeUseFeatureFlag}` to stub behavior.
- Default usability: because the context’s default is the real implementation, app code can use `useFeatureFlag` even when no provider is present.

Provider usage:
```tsx
import { UseFeatureFlagContext } from '@state/featureFlags/hooks/useFeatureFlag/useFeatureFlag';

const mockUseFeatureFlag: typeof UseFeatureFlagContext._currentValue = (name, defaultValue, accountId) => {
  // custom logic, e.g., look up from fixtures
  return myFixture[name] ?? defaultValue ?? false;
};

const App = () => (
  <UseFeatureFlagContext.Provider value={mockUseFeatureFlag}>
    <YourRoutes />
  </UseFeatureFlagContext.Provider>
);
```
Any `useFeatureFlag` call under that provider will use the supplied function instead of `_useFeatureFlag`; outside a provider it falls back to the default implementation.

