payload.message:
In a test, wrap the component under a `UseFeatureFlagContext.Provider` and pass a substitute function. Every `useFeatureFlag` call under that tree uses your function instead of the real hook.

Example with React Testing Library:

```tsx
import { render, screen } from '@testing-library/react';
import { UseFeatureFlagContext } from '@state/featureFlags/hooks/useFeatureFlag/useFeatureFlag';
import MyComponent from './MyComponent';

const fakeUseFeatureFlag = (name: any, defaultValue?: any) => {
  const overrides = { coolFeature: true, otherFlag: false };
  return overrides[name] ?? defaultValue ?? false;
};

test('uses injected flags', () => {
  render(
    <UseFeatureFlagContext.Provider value={fakeUseFeatureFlag}>
      <MyComponent />
    </UseFeatureFlagContext.Provider>
  );

  expect(screen.getByText(/cool feature is on/i)).toBeInTheDocument();
});
```

Key points:
- Provide your own function via `value`; signature matches the real one `(name, defaultValue, accountId?) => result`.
- Components still call `useFeatureFlag(...)`, but the context supplies your injected function.
- Outside a provider, the hook falls back to the default implementation defined in the file.

